-- tests/integration/mut_receiver_static_twin.iron
-- Phase 79 MUT-05 twin of mut_receiver_grammar.iron.
-- Same object, same method names, same receiver types, same param types,
-- same return types — ONLY the `mut` keyword is absent from the Counter
-- receiver bindings.
--
-- Phase 79 role (when it shipped): byte-identical C signature vs
-- mut_receiver_grammar.iron — proving `mut` was purely a surface grammar
-- annotation with zero lowering effect. Both .expected files were
-- byte-identical (`0\n500000`).
--
-- Phase 80 role (current): pure-superset control. `mut` is now a hard
-- semantic gate. MUT-03 (Plan 80-02) rejects field mutation inside an
-- immutable-receiver method body at compile time, so this twin can no
-- longer attempt `c.n = c.n + 1` inside `func (c: Counter) bump()` —
-- the compiler emits E0234. The twin is updated to a read-only shape
-- that preserves its original purpose: prove non-mut receiver-form
-- methods still compile and run cleanly under Phase 80 enforcement,
-- with the same (`0\n500000`) output the Phase 79 by-value baseline
-- produced. bump() is now a no-op — same call structure, same observed
-- `c.n == 0` result, no illegal field mutation.
--
-- Expected output stays `0\n500000`. The sister file
-- mut_receiver_grammar.expected is `3\n500000` (Phase 80 MUT-07
-- positive-space: mut-receiver Counter.bump() observably mutates).

import time

object Counter {
    var n: Int
}

-- No `mut` keyword -- v2.1 receiver-form (val-default binding).
-- Body is a no-op: MUT-03 (Plan 80-02) would emit E0234 if we tried
-- `c.n = c.n + 1` here. The call structure (three bump() invocations)
-- is preserved to keep the test shape parallel to the sister file.
-- A local read of c.n keeps the function from being elided by the
-- backend (empty bodies emit no symbol), while still not mutating.
func (c: Counter) bump() {
    val _unused: Int = c.n
}

func (c: Counter) get() -> Int {
    return c.n
}

func main() {
    val c = Counter(0)
    c.bump()
    c.bump()
    c.bump()
    println("{c.get()}")

    val timer = Time.Timer(1000.0)
    timer.update(500.0)
    println("{timer.elapsed_ms}")
}
